{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "In the multi-species kinetic literature there exist in fact several recent papers revolving around this topic, but they are mostly exploiting a non-constructive approach based on Weyl's perturbation theorem.",
    "We mention for example the first compactness result for the linearized collision operator modeling inert monatomic mixtures [18] and similar strategies developed to analyse more elaborate linearized operators for collisions inside of polyatomic gases [5,6,7,8,17,24], also involving chemical reactions [9,26].",
    "The interested reader can consult the reviews [10,19] detailing the literature and techniques revolving around these recent outcomes.",
    "Results on quantitative coercivity estimates are instead less prevalent, pertain solely to the non-reactive setting (and to the case of Maxwellian, hard-potential and hard-sphere collision kernels with cutoff) and can be narrowed down to the works [21,28], which first obtained explicit bounds on the spectral gap of the linearization of Q EL, and [14] where it was proved that this spectral gap is stable under small local non-equilibrium perturbations of the global Maxwellian M ∞, in connection with the rigorous derivation of the inert Maxwell-Stefan model [15,16].Following the ideas developed in [21,28], we approach the problem by tackling separately the linearized counterparts of Q EL and Q CH.",
    "Starting from the explicit coercivity estimate that is known to hold for the linearized multi-species elastic operator, we show that its spectral gap is not perturbed too much by the presence of the reactive component Q CH."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "We mention for example the first compactness result for the linearized collision operator modeling inert monatomic mixtures [18] and similar strategies developed to analyse more elaborate linearized operators for collisions inside of polyatomic gases [5,6,7,8,17,24], also involving chemical reactions [9,26].",
    "The interested reader can consult the reviews [10,19] detailing the literature and techniques revolving around these recent outcomes.",
    "Results on quantitative coercivity estimates are instead less prevalent, pertain solely to the non-reactive setting (and to the case of Maxwellian, hard-potential and hard-sphere collision kernels with cutoff) and can be narrowed down to the works [21,28], which first obtained explicit bounds on the spectral gap of the linearization of Q EL, and [14] where it was proved that this spectral gap is stable under small local non-equilibrium perturbations of the global Maxwellian M ∞, in connection with the rigorous derivation of the inert Maxwell-Stefan model [15,16].Following the ideas developed in [21,28], we approach the problem by tackling separately the linearized counterparts of Q EL and Q CH."
